===Etymology 1===
Late 17th century, of {{unk|en|title=unknown}} origin;

* Possibly allied to {{der|en|cy|moedro|t=to worry or bother}}, though according to the GPC, the latter is borrowed from English.<ref>{{R:cy:GPC|moedro}}</ref>
* Alternatively, possibly tied to {{cog|cy|meidda|t=to beg for whey}}, from {{m|cy|maidd|t=whey}}.
* Perhaps from {{cog|cy|meiddio|t=to dare or venture}}, a variant of {{m|cy|beiddio|t=to dare}}.

Bear in mind that the "dd" in Welsh corresponds in sound to the "th" in mither, and English also has [[moider]] and [[moither]].

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/ˈmaɪðə(ɹ)/}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive|Northern England|especially|_|Manchester}} To make an [[unnecessary]] [[fuss]], [[moan]], [[bother]].
#*{{quote-journal|en|text=The European Commission is pondering how to compel phone companies to come up with a universal plug for their chargers. Apple, which uses its own design for its charger cables, is '''mithering''' about the change.|6 February 2020||The parable of the plug|The Economist}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|Northern England|especially|_|Manchester}} To [[pester]] or [[irritate]] someone. Usually directed at [[children]].
#: {{ux|en|Will you stop '''mithering''' me!}}

